[00:01.28]	+ the other, BASSIANUS, LAVINIA, and others]
[00:01.71]SATURNINUS	So, Bassianus, you have play'd your prize:
[00:05.00]	God give you joy, sir, of your gallant bride!
[00:08.50]BASSIANUS	And you of yours, my lord! I say no more,
[00:11.72]	Nor wish no less; and so, I take my leave.
[00:15.01]SATURNINUS	Traitor, if Rome have law or we have power,
[00:18.44]	Thou and thy faction shall repent this rape.
[00:22.02]BASSIANUS	Rape, call you it, my lord, to seize my own,
[00:25.38]	My truth-betrothed love and now my wife?
[00:28.67]	But let the laws of Rome determine all;
[00:31.89]	Meanwhile I am possess'd of that is mine.
[00:35.25]SATURNINUS	'Tis good, sir: you are very short with us;
[00:38.54]	But, if we live, we'll be as sharp with you.
[00:41.97]BASSIANUS	My lord, what I have done, as best I may,
[00:45.19]	Answer I must and shall do with my life.
[00:48.48]	Only thus much I give your grace to know:
[00:51.84]	By all the duties that I owe to Rome,
[00:54.91]	This noble gentleman, Lord Titus here,
[00:57.99]	Is in opinion and in honour wrong'd;
[01:00.99]	That in the rescue of Lavinia
[01:03.57]	With his own hand did slay his youngest son,
[01:07.14]	In zeal to you and highly moved to wrath
[01:10.50]	To be controll'd in that he frankly gave:
[01:13.86]	Receive him, then, to favor, Saturnine,
[01:16.87]	That hath express'd himself in all his deeds
[01:20.51]	A father and a friend to thee and Rome.
[01:23.73]TITUS ANDRONICUS	Prince Bassianus, leave to plead my deeds:
[01:27.09]	'Tis thou and those that have dishonour'd me.
[01:30.67]	Rome and the righteous heavens be my judge,
[01:34.17]	How I have loved and honour'd Saturnine!
[01:37.46]TAMORA	My worthy lord, if ever Tamora
[01:40.04]	Were gracious in those princely eyes of thine,
[01:43.75]	Then hear me speak in indifferently for all;
[01:47.33]	And at my suit, sweet, pardon what is past.
[01:50.69]SATURNINUS	What, madam! be dishonour'd openly,
[01:53.48]	And basely put it up without revenge?
[01:56.55]TAMORA	Not so, my lord; the gods of Rome forfend
[01:59.84]	I should be author to dishonour you!
[02:02.85]	But on mine honour dare I undertake
[02:05.85]	For good Lord Titus' innocence in all;
[02:08.92]	Whose fury not dissembled speaks his griefs:
[02:12.50]	Then, at my suit, look graciously on him;
[02:15.72]	Lose not so noble a friend on vain suppose,
[02:19.22]	Nor with sour looks afflict his gentle heart.
[02:22.87]	[Aside to SATURNINUS] My lord, be ruled by me,
